messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
Um, across from 4709, 40th Avenue.
Um, yeah, 4709.
Okay, what city is that, ma'am?
I'm in Hyattsville, sorry.
And what's your name?
Cynthia.
Cynthia? Tell me exactly what happened.
It's a fire. The house is on fire.
Okay, the house is on fire?
Yeah.
Is everyone out?
Not everyone's out.
Not everyone's out?
No.
Alright, hold on one second, okay. The house is catching fire fast. Is it a single-family home?
Yes.
Do you know how many floors or stories there are?
Two.
And you said there are people inside?
Yes. Children.
The call is in. Stay on the line. I need to know how many are inside, do you know?
I don't know. I'm across the street.
Do you know how many children live in that house?
Uh, three, I think.
Do you know exactly?
I can't get any closer.
Who's that screaming? Are they the owners?
Yes.
Can you ask them if there's anybody inside and where?
Martha, who's inside? Where? I'm on the phone with 911.
He's in there.
How many people are still inside?
He's not listening to me. His wife is trying to get back inside.
Okay, tell him not to go back inside.
Just try to find out who's inside and where they are.
He's not listening to me. I can't get any closer because the fire is growing.
The call is in, help is on the way, okay? Whatever information you can gather is going to be helpful to us.
Do you know what floor is on fire?
It's the first floor.
What was that?
A power line. It's burning off the house.
Did it go down or is it burning?
It's disconnected from the house.
Okay, you said it was the first floor on fire?
Yeah.
My roommate, Don Watson, is on the line too. I guess he called 911.
He's calling 911 as well? Alright, if you can, find out from the owners where the people are inside. We need to know now. We have everyone on the way.
Okay, I'm trying to get back around the side of the neighbor's house.
Okay. We have the fire department on the way.
Are you still there?
I'm here.
If it is safe to do so, keep bystanders away from the area.
Marcos, where are you? Can everybody get out? Where is everyone?
His daughter's inside.
The daughter?
The daughter.
How old is the daughter?
She's less than 12.
Do you know where inside they are?
No, I can't get closer. I'm just at the neighbor's house.
The address you gave me, is that the house on fire?
Yes, it is.
And it's 4709?
Yeah.
Do you know where the daughter is?
No, he won't say.
The kids are upstairs.
The kids are upstairs?
Yes.
So there may be two children upstairs?
Yes, there's definitely one child upstairs.
The fire department's coming. Please don't go back inside.
Is that the mother?
The mother and the father.
The neighbor on the other side just came over and said there are two children out of the house.
Okay, so you don't know if anyone is inside of the house?
No, I called you just after the fire started.
Do you know what caused it?
No.
Where are the flames coming from? Are they in the front or back of the house?
The front.
And you said it was the first floor?
Yeah.
Is the first floor below ground or above ground?
It's on the ground.
Okay, you should be seeing the fire department.
Do you see them?
Yes.
Make sure to let them know where and how many are inside.
Okay, everybody's in the backyard. I'm going around to the front.
Try to get to them and let them know there are kids inside.
I'm yelling to the firemen, two kids upstairs.
Okay, you told them?
Yeah. Let me make sure they understood.
Now, the power line that blew up, do you still see it?
Yeah.
Is it on the ground or up in the air?
It's on the ground.
Can you point that out to some of the firefighters so they know?
Okay.
Okay, someone is with you now?
Where are the power lines down, ma'am? On what side of the house?
On the side of the house, facing the right.
Someone sees it, they are all over it.
Alright, everybody's there?
Yeah.
Okay, are you okay?
Yep, I'm fine.
Alright.
Okay, bye.
Okay, bye.
